{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q4sDSF9bV7PAoL9raxBDLZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the spark-pi namespace. Let me analyze the findings:\n\n**RBAC:**\n1. `spark-pi` ServiceAccount exists — GOOD\n2. `spark-pi-role` Role exists with rules for pods, services, configmaps, and PVCs — GOOD\n3. `spark-pi-role-binding` RoleBinding binds the role to the `spark-pi` service account — GOOD\n4. The `default` service account still exists (Kubernetes creates this automatically)\n5. All resources use `spark-pi` service account (not `default`) — GOOD\n6. The role grants `delete`, `update`, and `patch` verbs which is broader than needed for a read-only cluster, and includes PVC permissions that don't appear to be in use\n\n**Resource Limits:**\n- Both spark-master and spark-worker have reasonable CPU and memory limits (500m/1Gi) with appropriate requests (200m/512Mi) — GOOD\n- The spark-pi job limits are still being reviewed\n\n**Image Provenance:**\n- Using specific version tags like `apache/spark:3.5.3` rather than `latest` is good practice, but there's no digest pinning with SHA256 hashes, which means a tag mutation or registry compromise could introduce unexpected code changes\n\n**Security Context:**\n- All three components (spark-master, spark-worker, and spark-pi job) have empty security contexts at both pod and container levels, leaving them without hardening like runAsNonRoot or read-only filesystems\n\n**Network Policies:**\n- No NetworkPolicy is defined, so pods can communicate freely with each other and have unrestricted egress\n\n**Job Configuration:**\n- The spark-pi job is appropriately configured with `backoffLimit: 0` and `restartPolicy: Never` for a single-run execution, and it uses a dedicated service account rather than the default\n\n**Summary of Findings:**\n\nPASSING:\n1. Dedicated `spark-pi` ServiceAccount created (not using default)\n2. RBAC Role (`spark-pi-role`) scoped to namespace with specific resource types\n3. R\n\nGAPS:\n1. No pod-level or container-level securityContext on any workload — missing `runAsNonRoot`, `allowPrivilegeEscalation: false`, capabilities drop, and `readOnlyRootFilesystem`\n2. Image uses a mutable tag (`3.5.3`) instead of being pinned by digest, so the image could be replaced unexpectedly\n3. No NetworkPolicy restricts pod communication, allowing unrestricted traffic within and outside the namespace\n4. RBAC Role grants `delete`, `update`, and `patch` verbs on pods, which is broader than Spark typically needs\n\n, plus unnecessary access to `persistentvolumeclaims` that aren't used\n5. No namespace-level LimitRange or ResourceQuota, despite individual container limits being set\n6. `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent` can serve stale images if a tag changes without digest pinning\n\nNow I'm putting together the audit findings and creating the ConfigMap to document these issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1554,"cache_read_input_tokens":31989,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1554},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ecacabe8-c22b-41a6-a2fc-48c003317577","uuid":"70f1540a-22bb-44d0-9660-5eaa6fd8069b","request_id":"req_011CcRK2aPN2P3T4gnd2kFhJ"}
